Class.terms:description: A biopolymer is an organic polymer using biological components.
Class.rdfs:label: biopolymer

Class.terms:description: A monomer is a submolecule that is proper part of some polymer, and is a building block for such polymer.
Class.rdfs:label: monomer

Class.terms:description: A polymer is a molecule composed of a connected set of monomeric residues.
Class.rdfs:label: polymer

Class.terms:description: A lipid residue is a part of an organic molecule that was derived from a lipid molecule.
Class.rdfs:label: lipid residue

Class.terms:description: A data storage device is a device that is capable of storing information.
Class.rdfs:label: data storage device

Class.terms:description: A solid-state drive (SSD) is a data storage device that uses solid-state memory to store persistent data.
Class.rdfs:label: solid state hard drive

Class.terms:description: A hard disk drive (HDD) is a non-volatile, random access device for digital data. It features rotating rigid platters on a motor-driven spindle within a protective enclosure. Data is magnetically read and written on the platter by read/write heads that float on a film of air above the platters.
Class.rdfs:label: hard disk drive

Class.terms:description: A sound wave is a mechanical wave that is an oscillation of pressure transmitted through a solid, liquid, or gas, composed of frequencies within the range of hearing.
Class.rdfs:label: sound wave

Class.terms:description: A chemical functional group is a covalently connected part of a molecule which normally confer specific chemical properties.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical functional group

Class.terms:description: A wave is a physical entity that travels through space and time, consist of oscillations or vibrations and may be accompanied by the transfer of energy.
Class.rdfs:label: wave

Class.terms:description: A primer is a nucleic acid that enables the synthesis of a complement strand of DNA by binding to it and acting as a point of transcription initiation.
Class.rdfs:label: primer

Class.terms:description: A non-protein coding RNA (ncRNA) gene is a gene that encodes for a RNA transcript that is not further translated into a protein product.
Class.rdfs:label: non-protein coding RNA (ncRNA) gene

Class.terms:description: A chromosome is a molecular complex of circular or linear DNA and bound proteins.
Class.rdfs:label: chromosome

Class.terms:description: A radio receiver is a communication device that receives its input from an antenna, uses electronic filters to separate a wanted radio signal from all other signals picked up by this antenna, amplifies it to a level suitable for further processing, and finally converts through demodulation and decoding the signal into a form usable for the consumer, such as sound, pictures, digital data, measurement values, navigational positions.
Class.rdfs:label: radio receiver

Class.terms:description: The telephone is a communications device that transmits and receives sounds, and are minimally composed of a microphone to speak into, a speaker'which reproduces the voice of the other person and a ringer which makes a sound to alert the owner when a call is coming in.
Class.rdfs:label: telephone

Class.terms:description: A radar is an object-detection system which uses radio waves to determine the range, altitude, direction, or speed of objects.
Class.rdfs:label: radar

Class.terms:description: A device is usually a constructed tool.
Class.rdfs:label: device

Class.terms:description: A communication device is a device that facilitates the transmission of information through encoded in an audio or digital signal between a sender and a receiver.
Class.rdfs:label: communication device

Class.terms:description: A gene that contains an open reading frame which codes for a protein.
Class.rdfs:label: protein coding gene

Class.terms:description: A gene that codes for a functional RNA molecule.
Class.rdfs:label: functional rna coding gene

Class.terms:description: A predicted gene is a gene that was identified through computational method but has not been experimentally validated.
Class.rdfs:label: predicted gene

Class.terms:description: A pseudo gene is a region of a nucleic acid that either cannot be transcribed, or its RNA transcript cannot be translated.
Class.rdfs:label: pseudogene

Class.terms:description: An experimentally validated gene is a gene whose existence has been demonstrated through experimental methods.
Class.rdfs:label: validated gene

Class.terms:description: A sample is a limited quantity of something (e.g. an individual or set of individuals from a population, or a portion of a substance) to be used for testing, analysis, inspection, investigation, demonstration, or trial use.
Class.rdfs:label: sample

Class.terms:description: A liquid solution is a heterogeneous substance in a liquid state.
Class.rdfs:label: liquid solution

Class.terms:description: double stranded nucleic acid is a molecular complex composed of two weakly connected deoxyribonucleic acids.
Class.rdfs:label: double stranded DNA

Class.terms:description: A nucleic acid strand is a single-stranded nucleic acid that is part of a double stranded nucleic acid complex.
Class.rdfs:label: nucleic acid strand

Class.terms:description: The positive nucleic acid strand refers to the strand that is to be read 5' to 3'.
Class.rdfs:label: positive nucleic acid strand

Class.terms:description: The negative nucleic acid strand is the strand that is that is complimentary to the forward strand and appears from 3' to 5'.
Class.rdfs:label: negative nucleic acid strand

Class.terms:description: double stranded nucleic acid is a molecular complex composed of two weakly connected nucleic acids.
Class.rdfs:label: double stranded nucleic acid

Class.terms:description: double stranded nucleic acid is a molecular complex composed of two weakly connected ribonucleic acids.
Class.rdfs:label: double stranded RNA

Class.terms:description: A ribosomal RNA gene is a gene that codes for a ribosomal RNA molecule.
Class.rdfs:label: ribosomal RNA gene

Class.terms:description: The 5' splice site is the terminal region of an exon that is 5' to the intron that is to be excised.
Class.rdfs:label: 5' splice site

Class.terms:description: The 3' splice site is the terminal region of an exon that is 3' to the intron that is to be excised.
Class.rdfs:label: 3' splice site

Class.terms:description: An amino acid is an organic molecule composed of a carbon bonded to four different groups: a carboxyl group, an amino group, an R group, and a hydrogen atom. In the case of glycine, the R group is another hydrogen atom.
Class.rdfs:label: amino acid

Class.terms:description: A cisregulatory element is a DNA sequence located on the same DNA strand or chromosome as the gene whose expression it affects.
Class.rdfs:label: cis regulatory element

Class.terms:description: A trans-regulatory element is a DNA sequence associated with the regulation of a gene located outside the genomic region supporting the corresponding structural DNA region of the trans-regulatory element (i.e., a different DNA strand or different chromosome).
Class.rdfs:label: trans-regulatory element

Class.terms:description: A small cytoplasmic RNA (scRNA) gene is a gene that encodes a small (7S; 129 nucleotides) RNA molecule found in the cytosol and rough endoplasmic reticulum that are normally associated with proteins that are involved in specific selection and transport of other proteins.
Class.rdfs:label: small cytoplasmic RNA (scRNA) gene

Class.terms:description: A small nuclear RNA (snRNA) gene is a gene that encodes a small niuclear RNA molecule.
Class.rdfs:label: small nuclear RNA (snRNA) gene

Class.terms:description: A small nucleolar RNA (snoRNA) gene is a gene that encodes a small RNA that are associated with the eukaryotic nucleus as components of small nucleolar ribonucleoproteins.
Class.rdfs:label: small nucleolar RNA (snoRNA) gene

Class.terms:description: A transfer RNA (tRNA) gene is a gene that codes for a tRNA used in the translation of a messenger RNA (mRNA) to produce a protein product.
Class.rdfs:label: transfer RNA (tRNA) gene

Class.terms:description: A small cytoplasmic RNA (scRNA) molecule is a small (7S; 129 nucleotides) RNA molecule found in the cytosol and rough endoplasmic reticulum that are normally associated with proteins that are involved in specific selection and transport of other proteins.
Class.rdfs:label: small cytoplasmic RNA (scRNA)

Class.terms:description: A transfer RNA (tRNA) is an RNA molecule that aids in the translation of a messenger RNA (mRNA) to produce a protein product.
Class.rdfs:label: transfer RNA (tRNA)

Class.terms:description: A small nuclear RNA (snRNA) is a small RNA molecule that is located in the nucleus of a cell.
Class.rdfs:label: small nuclear RNA (snRNA)

Class.terms:description: A small nucleolar RNA (snoRNA) is a small RNA that are associated with the eukaryotic nucleus as components of small nucleolar ribonucleoproteins.
Class.rdfs:label: small nucleolar RNA (snoRNA)

Class.terms:description: A non-protein coding RNA (ncRNA) is a RNA molecular that cannot be used as a template for generating a protein product.
Class.rdfs:label: non-protein coding RNA (ncRNA)

Class.terms:description: A data collection device is a device that collects information about one or more objects.
Class.rdfs:label: data collection device

Class.terms:description: A mass spectrometer is a device that identifies ions based on their mass to charge ratio using an electromagnetic field.
Class.rdfs:label: mass spectrometer

Class.terms:description: A microarray device is a device that identifies the binding of a target substance to a physically immobile substrate placed in an array or lattice.
Class.rdfs:label: microarray device

Class.terms:description: A nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) device is a device that applies a magnetic field to perturb nuclei with an odd number of protons and/or of neutrons in order to hav them absort and re-emit electromagnetic radiation.
Class.rdfs:label: nmr device

Class.terms:description: a single nucleotide variation (SNV) is a nucleotide residue that is a variant compared to some reference nucleic acid sequence.
Class.rdfs:label: single nucleotide polymorphism

Class.terms:description: an analyte is a substance or chemical constituent of interest in an analytical procedure.
Class.rdfs:label: analyte

Class.dc:description: A protein domain is a part of a protein that maintains its structure and function independently of the rest of the protein.
Class.rdfs:label: protein domain

Class.dc:description: a genomic sequence variant is part of a nucleic acid which is compositionally different than another reference genomic part.
Class.rdfs:label: genomic sequence variant

Class.dc:description: A protein coding sequence (CDS) is the region of DNA that is translated to form proteins. The CDS refers to those nucleotides (concatenated exons) that can be divided into codons which are actually translated into amino acids by the ribosomal translation machinery.
Class.rdfs:label: protein coding sequence

Class.dc:description: A biologic, also known as a biologic medical product, biological, or biopharmaceutical, is any pharmaceutical drug product manufactured in, extracted from, or semisynthesized from biological sources.
Class.rdfs:label: biologic

Class.dc:description: a post-translational modification is a part of a protein that was added, removed, or modified as a result of a chemical reaction after synthesis.
Class.rdfs:label: post-translational modification

Class.terms:description: a carbohydrate is an organic molecule composed of one or more monosaccharides.
Class.rdfs:label: carbohydrate

Class.dc:description: A microRNA (abbreviated miRNA) is a small non-coding RNA molecule (containing about 22 nucleotides) found in plants, animals and some viruses, that functions in RNA silencing and post-transcriptional regulation of gene expression.
Class.rdfs:label: microRNA (miRNA)

Class.terms:description: A chemical entity is a material entity that pertains to chemistry.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical entity

Class.terms:description: A weak submolecular component is a submolecular component that weakly connects submolecular components.
Class.rdfs:label: weak submolecular component

Class.terms:description: A polypeptide is an organic polymer composed of amino acid residues.
Class.rdfs:label: polypeptide

Class.terms:description: A nucleic acid is an organic polymer composed of a sequence of nucleotide residues.
Class.rdfs:label: nucleic acid

Class.terms:description: A ribonucleic acid is an organic polymer composed of a sequence of ribonucleotide residues.
Class.rdfs:label: ribonucleic acid

Class.terms:description: A deoxyribonucleic acid is an organic polymer composed of a sequence of deoxyribonucleotide residues.
Class.rdfs:label: deoxyribonucleic acid

Class.terms:description: A lipid is a water-insoluable organic molecule.
Class.rdfs:label: lipid

Class.terms:description: A submolecular entity is a part of a molecular entity.
Class.rdfs:label: submolecular entity

Class.terms:description: An oligosaccharide is an organic polymer composed of monosaccharides joined by glycosidic bonds.
Class.rdfs:label: oligosaccharide

Class.terms:description: genetic polymorphism is the description of a difference in genetic composition at some location.
Class.rdfs:label: genetic polymorphism

Class.terms:description: A monosaccharide is an organic polymer that consists of a single polyhydroxy aldehyde or ketone group.
Class.rdfs:label: monosaccharide

Class.terms:description: A hydrogen bond is a weak submolecular interaction formed between a hydrogen atom and a electronegative atom.
Class.rdfs:label: hydrogen bond

Class.terms:description: A cation pi interaction is an ionic interaction between the localized negative charge of Ï€ orbital electrons, located above and below the plane of an aromatic ring, and a positive charge.
Class.rdfs:label: cation pi interaction

Class.terms:description: A gene is part of a nucleic acid that contains all the necessary elements to encode a functional transcript.
Class.rdfs:label: gene

Class.terms:description: A chemical element is a (effectively) homogeneous substance composed of one type of atom.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical element

Class.terms:description: A drug is a chemical entity that regulates a biological process.
Class.rdfs:label: drug

Class.terms:description: A pharmaceutical preparation is a chemical substance approved for use in the medical diagnosis, cure, treatment, or prevention of disease.
Class.rdfs:label: pharmaceutical preparation

Class.terms:description: A haplotype is one of a set of genomic sequence variants.
Class.rdfs:label: haplotype

Class.terms:description: A protein is an organic polymer that is composed of one or more linear polymers of amino acids.
Class.rdfs:label: protein

Class.terms:description: An atom is composed of a core of protons and/or neutrons which may be surrounded by a cloud of electrons.
Class.rdfs:label: atom

Class.terms:description: A base pair is a weak molecular interaction composed of hydrogen bonds between nucleobases.
Class.rdfs:label: base pair

Class.terms:description: A strong submolecular component is a submolecular component that strongly connects submolecular components.
Class.rdfs:label: strong submolecular component

Class.terms:description: The five prime untranslated region (5' UTR) is a section of messenger RNA (mRNA) and the DNA that codes for it that starts at the +1 position (where transcription begins) and ends one nucleotide before the start codon (usually AUG) of the coding region.
Class.rdfs:label: 5' untranslated region

Class.terms:description: A three prime untranslated region (3'-UTR) is the section of messenger RNA (mRNA) that immediately follows the translation termination codon.
Class.rdfs:label: 3' untranslated region

Class.terms:description: An organic submolecule is connected region of a molecule.
Class.rdfs:label: organic submolecule

Class.terms:description: An organic molecular entity is a chemical entity composed of organic atoms (at least carbon, hydrogen, and optionally oxygen, phosphorus, nitrogen)
Class.rdfs:label: organic molecule

Class.terms:description: An open reading frame (ORF) is a part of a gene that encodes a protein but does not contain a stop codon.
Class.rdfs:label: open reading frame

Class.terms:description: An amino acid residue is a part of a molecule that is derived from an amino acid molecule.
Class.rdfs:label: amino acid residue

Class.terms:description: A nucleotide residue is a part of a molecule that derives from a nucleotide.
Class.rdfs:label: nucleotide residue

Class.terms:description: A poison is a drug that is harzardous or toxic to an organism when ingested at a certain quantity.
Class.rdfs:label: poison

Class.terms:description: An active ingredient is a molecular entity that exhibits biological activity.
Class.rdfs:label: active ingredient

Class.terms:description: An operon is a collection of contiguous genes transcribed as a single (polycistronic) mRNA.
Class.rdfs:label: operon

Class.terms:description: A gene regulatory component is a gene component that exerts a regulatory function.
Class.rdfs:label: gene regulatory component

Class.terms:description: A gene enhancer is a short region of DNA that can be bound with proteins to enhance transcription levels of genes in a gene cluster.
Class.rdfs:label: gene enhancer

Class.terms:description: Aninactive ingredient is a molecular entity that does not exhibit biological activity.
Class.rdfs:label: inactive ingredient

Class.terms:description: A deoxyribonucleic acid template is a deoxyribonucleic acid that provides the template to synthesize a complementary strand of DNA through transcription.
Class.rdfs:label: deoxyribonucleic acid template

Class.terms:description: A deoxyribonucleic acid primer is a deoxyribonucleic acid that enables the synthesis of a complement strand of DNA by binding to it and acting as a point of transcription initiation.
Class.rdfs:label: deoxyribonucleic acid primer

Class.terms:description: An RNA transcript component is a region of an RNA transcript.
Class.rdfs:label: RNA transcript component

Class.terms:description: A mature RNA is a ribonucleic acid that contains an untranslated region (UTR) and protein coding sequence and lacks introns.
Class.rdfs:label: mature mRNA

Class.terms:description: Precursor mRNA (pre-mRNA) is a single strand of messenger ribonucleic acid (mRNA) that is synthesized from a DNA template throught transcription.
Class.rdfs:label: pre-mRNA

Class.terms:description: An mRNA splice variant is an mRNA molecule that varies from another mRNA molecule of the same gene origin but having a different final sequence due to differences in its assembly from splice sites.
Class.rdfs:label: mRNA splice variant

Class.terms:description: A messenger RNA is a ribonucleic acid that contains an untranslated region (UTR) and protein coding sequence and lacks introns.
Class.rdfs:label: messenger RNA

Class.terms:description: A gene that is located on DNA.
Class.rdfs:label: dna gene

Class.terms:description: A gene that is located on RNA.
Class.rdfs:label: rna gene

Class.terms:description: An allele is one of a set of sequence variants of a gene.
Class.rdfs:label: allele

Class.terms:description: A carbohydrate residue is a part of a molecule that was derived from a monosaccharide molecule.
Class.rdfs:label: carbohydrate residue

Class.terms:description: A nucleic acid part is a component of a nucleic acid.
Class.rdfs:label: nucleic acid part

Class.terms:description: A deoxyribonucleotide residue is a part of a molecule that derives from a deoxyribonucleotide.
Class.rdfs:label: deoxyribonucleotide residue

Class.terms:description: A ribonucleotide residue is a part of a molecule that derives from a ribonucleotide.
Class.rdfs:label: ribonucleotide residue

Class.terms:description: A pharmaceutical component is a part of a pharmaceutical preparation.
Class.rdfs:label: pharmaceutical component

Class.terms:description: A covalently connected molecular entity is the mereological sum of a collection of covalently bonded atoms.
Class.rdfs:label: covalently connected entity

Class.terms:description: A chemical complex is a chemical entity composed of a weakly connected ions or molecules.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical complex

Class.terms:description: An enzyme is a protein or protein complex that realizes its disposition to covalently modify some molecule during a chemical reaction.
Class.rdfs:label: enzyme

Class.terms:description: A catalyst is a molecule that has the capability to reduce the activation energy of a reaction and hence increase the overall rate of reaction.
Class.rdfs:label: catalyst

Class.terms:description: An organic polymer is an organic molecule composed of connected set of monomeric units.
Class.rdfs:label: organic polymer

Class.terms:description: A reagent is a substance that is added to a system in order to bring about a chemical reaction, or added to see if a reaction occurs.
Class.rdfs:label: reagent

Class.terms:description: A specimen is a portion of material for use in testing, examination, or study.
Class.rdfs:label: specimen

Class.terms:description: A buffer is a dissolved chemical substance that resists change in pH upon addition of small amounts of acid or base.
Class.rdfs:label: buffer

Class.terms:description: A solvent is a substance that can dissolve other substances (solutes).
Class.rdfs:label: solvent

Class.terms:description: A solute is a substance that becomes dissolved in a solvent.
Class.rdfs:label: solute

Class.terms:description: An antigen is a chemical entity that can be bound by a major histocompatibility complex (MHC) and presented to a T-cell receptor.
Class.rdfs:label: antigen

Class.terms:description: A receptor molecule is a molecule that has the capability to bind to a signal and propogate a response to that signal.
Class.rdfs:label: receptor

Class.terms:description: A centrifugation pellet is a solid substance that forms as a result of compaction by a centrifuge.
Class.rdfs:label: centrifugation pellet

Class.terms:description: A supernatent is a liquid substance that remains after centrifugation.
Class.rdfs:label: supernatant

Class.terms:description: A centrifugation substance is a substance that is the target or product of centrifugation.
Class.rdfs:label: centrifugation substance

Class.terms:description: A liquid solution component is a part of a liquid solution.
Class.rdfs:label: liquid solution component

Class.terms:description: A placebo is a medically ineffectual treatment for a medical condition intended to deceive the recipient.
Class.rdfs:label: placebo

Class.terms:description: A low barrier hydrogen bond is a shorter, stronger hydrogen bond that is formed between both heteroatoms.
Class.rdfs:label: low barrier hydrogen bond

Class.terms:description: A molecular activator is a molecular regulator that realizes its disposition to conformationally change a target molecule and increase its functionality.
Class.rdfs:label: activator

Class.terms:description: A molecular inhibitor is a molecular regulator that realizes its disposition to conformationally change a target molecule and decrease its functionality.
Class.rdfs:label: inhibitor

Class.terms:description: A molecular regulator is a molecule that regulates the function of another chemical entity.
Class.rdfs:label: molecular regulator

Class.terms:description: A signal transducer is a molecule that responds to and amplifies a signal in a signalling system.
Class.rdfs:label: signal transducer

Class.terms:description: A signal is an object that initiates a sequence of events.
Class.rdfs:label: signal

Class.terms:description: A mesenger is a molecule involved in either signal detection or signal propagation from receptors on the cell surface to target molecules inside the cell, in the cytoplasm or nucleus.
Class.rdfs:label: messenger

Class.terms:description: A second messenger is a molecule that relay signals from receptors on the cell surface to target molecules inside the cell, in the cytoplasm or nucleus.
Class.rdfs:label: second messenger

Class.terms:description: A submolecule is a mereological sum of covalently bonded atoms.
Class.rdfs:label: submolecule

Class.terms:description: An intron is a region of a gene that is removed from the final protein open reading frame.
Class.rdfs:label: intron

Class.terms:description: A gene component is a component of a gene.
Class.rdfs:label: gene component

Class.terms:description: An exon is a nucleotide sequence encoded by a gene that remains present within the final mature RNA product of that gene after introns have been removed by RNA splicing.
Class.rdfs:label: exon

Class.terms:description: A gene promoter is a region of DNA that initiates transcription of a particular gene.
Class.rdfs:label: gene promoter

Class.terms:description: A start codon is the first codon of a messenger RNA (mRNA) transcript translated by a ribosome. The start codon is almost always preceded by an untranslated region 5' UTR.
Class.rdfs:label: start codon

Class.terms:description: A stop codon (or termination codon) is a nucleotide triplet within messenger RNA that signals a termination of translation.
Class.rdfs:label: stop codon

Class.terms:description: An RNA transcript is an RNA molecule that is produced from transcription of a nucleic acid template.
Class.rdfs:label: RNA transcript

Class.terms:description: A splice site is a region required for the excision of an intron and connection to another exon.
Class.rdfs:label: splice site

Class.terms:description: An acid is a molecular entity in solution capable of donating a hydron (Bronsted acid) or capable of forming a covalent bond with an electron pair (Lewis acid).
Class.rdfs:label: acid

Class.terms:description: A base is a molecular entity dissolved in a solvent that is capable of accepting a proton (Bronsted base) or forming a covalent bond with a hydron (Lewis base) .
Class.rdfs:label: base

Class.terms:description: An ion is an atom or molecule in which the total number of electrons is not equal to the total number of protons, giving it a net positive or negative electrical charge.
Class.rdfs:label: ion

Class.terms:description: A polar solvent is a solvent that exhibits a polar quality.
Class.rdfs:label: polar solvent

Class.terms:description: A non-polar solvent is a solvent that exhibits a non-polar quality.
Class.rdfs:label: nonpolar solvent

Class.terms:description: A heterogeneous substance is a chemical substance that is composed of more than one different kind of component.
Class.rdfs:label: heterogeneous substance

Class.terms:description: A homogeneous substance is a substance that is composed of a uniform type of entity.
Class.rdfs:label: homogeneous substance

Class.terms:description: An antibody (also known as immunoglobulins, abbreviated Ig) are gamma globulin proteins that are used by the immune system to identify and neutralize foreign objects. They are typically made of two large heavy chains and two small light chains.
Class.rdfs:label: antibody

Class.terms:description: An alpha helix is structural region of a protein that is characterized by 3.6 residues per turn, a translation of 1.5 angstroms along the helical axis in which backbone N-H groups form a hydrogen bond to the backbone carboxyl group of the amino acid four residues prior.
Class.rdfs:label: alpha helix

Class.terms:description: A beta strand is structural region of a protein that is characterized by a roughly planar sequence of amino acid residues forming hydrogen bonds between the N-O and the C=O of another part of the peptide and having their side chains perpendicular to the planar axis.
Class.rdfs:label: beta strand

Class.terms:description: A protein part is any submolecule of a protein.
Class.rdfs:label: protein part

Class.terms:description: An ionic interaction is a weak submolecular interaction between a charged submolecules.
Class.rdfs:label: ionic interaction

Class.terms:description: A protein complex is a molecular complex composed of at least two polypeptide chains.
Class.rdfs:label: protein complex

Class.terms:description: A single bond is a covalent bond between a pair of atoms in which one pair of electrons are shared.
Class.rdfs:label: single bond

Class.terms:description: A double bond is a covalent bond between a pair of atoms in which two pairs of electrons are shared.
Class.rdfs:label: double bond

Class.terms:description: A triple bond is a covalent bond between a pair of atoms in which three pairs of electrons are shared.
Class.rdfs:label: triple bond

Class.terms:description: An aromatic bond is an interaction between a set of atoms across which pairs of electrons are shared.
Class.rdfs:label: aromatic bond

Class.terms:description: A disulfide bond is a bond between two sulfur atoms.
Class.rdfs:label: disulfide bond

Class.terms:description: A dipole-dipole interaction is a weak submolecular interaction between strongly electronegative atoms.
Class.rdfs:label: dipole-dipole interaction

Class.terms:description: van der Waals' interaction is an a weak submolecular interaction between an instantaneous dipole and induced dipole.
Class.rdfs:label: van der Waals interaction

Class.terms:description: A base stack is a stabilizing interaction of DNA and RNA between spatially adjacent nucleotides and possibly involving London dispersion, hydrophobic and electrostatic forces.
Class.rdfs:label: base stack

Class.terms:description: A molecular complex is a chemical complex composed of weakly interacting molecular entities, and excludes bulk solvent.
Class.rdfs:label: molecular complex

Class.terms:description: A binary compound is a mereological maximum sum of two kinds of weakly connected entities.
Class.rdfs:label: binary compound

Class.terms:description: A ring is a submolecule with a circular topology.
Class.rdfs:label: ring

Class.terms:description: An aromatic ring is a ring in which the electrons are delocalized across all atoms in the ring.
Class.rdfs:label: aromatic ring

Class.terms:description: A heterocyclic ring is a ring containing a hetero atom.
Class.rdfs:label: heterocyclic ring

Class.terms:description: A homocyclic ring is a ring where the atoms are of a single type.
Class.rdfs:label: homocyclic ring

Class.terms:description: An ionic compound is a mereological maximal sum of weakly connected paired positive and negative ions.
Class.rdfs:label: ionic compound

Class.terms:description: An allotrope is a structural variant of a chemical element.
Class.rdfs:label: allotrope

Class.terms:description: A carbon allotrope is a chemical substance composed of carbon.
Class.rdfs:label: carbon allotrope

Class.terms:description: diamond is a carbon allotrope in which each carbon atom in diamond is covalently bonded to four other carbons in a tetrahedron. These tetrahedrons together form a 3-dimensional network of puckered six-membered rings of atoms.
Class.rdfs:label: diamond

Class.terms:description: graphite is an allotrope of carbon which is a conductor, and is the most stable form of solid carbon.
Class.rdfs:label: graphite

Class.terms:description: fullerene is a carbon allotrope which take the form of a hollow sphere, ellipsoid, or tube.
Class.rdfs:label: fullerene

Class.terms:description: aggregate of carbon nanorods is an allotrope of carbon considered to be the least compressible material known, as measured by its isothermal bulk modulus; aggregated diamond nanorods have a modulus of 491 gigapascals (GPa), while a conventional diamond has a modulus of 442 GPa. ADNRs are also 0.3% denser than regular diamond.
Class.rdfs:label: aggregated carbon nanorods

Class.terms:description: amorphous carbon is an allotrope of carbon that does not have any crystalline structure. As with all glassy materials, some short-range order can be observed, but there is no long-range pattern of atomic positions.
Class.rdfs:label: amorphous carbon

Class.terms:description: carbon nanofoam is an allotrope of carbon that consists of a low-density cluster-assembly of carbon atoms strung together in a loose three-dimensional web. Each cluster is about 6 nanometers wide and consists of about 4000 carbon atoms linked in graphite-like sheets that are given negative curvature by the inclusion of heptagons among the regular hexagonal pattern.
Class.rdfs:label: carbon nanofoam

Class.terms:description: chaoite is an allotrope of carbon that is slightly harder than graphite with a reflection colour of grey to white.
Class.rdfs:label: chaoite

Class.terms:description: glassy carbon is an allotrope of carbon which is widely used as an electrode material in electrochemistry, as well as for high temperature crucibles and as a component of some prosthetic devices.
Class.rdfs:label: glassy carbon

Class.terms:description: ionsdaleite is a hexagonal allotrope of the carbon allotrope diamond.
Class.rdfs:label: ionsdaleite

Class.terms:description: A covalent bond is a strong submolecular interaction between atoms.
Class.rdfs:label: covalent bond

Class.terms:description: A molecule is the mereological maximal sum of a collection of covalently bonded atoms.
Class.rdfs:label: molecule

Class.terms:description: A chemical substance is a chemical complex of weakly interacting molecular entities, and may include bulk solvent.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical substance
